TY  - JOUR
AU  - Drechsler, Itamar
AU  - Savov, Alexi
AU  - Schnabl, Philipp
T1  - The Deposits Channel of Monetary Policy*
PY  - 2017
Y1  - 2017/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjx019
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 132
IS  - 4
SP  - 1819
EP  - 1876
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We present a new channel for the transmission of monetary policy, the deposits channel. We show that when the Fed funds rate rises, banks widen the spreads they charge on deposits, and deposits flow out of the banking system. We present a model where this is due to market power in deposit markets. Consistent with the market power mechanism, deposit spreads increase more and deposits flow out more in concentrated markets. This is true even when we control for lending opportunities by only comparing different branches of the same bank. Since deposits are the main source of liquid assets for households, the deposits channel can explain the observed strong relationship between the liquidity premium and the Fed funds rate. Since deposits are also a uniquely stable funding source for banks, the deposits channel impacts bank lending. When the Fed funds rate rises, banks that raise deposits in concentrated markets contract their lending by more than other banks. Our estimates imply that the deposits channel can account for the entire transmission of monetary policy through bank balance sheets. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjx019
ER  - 



